Links: [{"title":"Zoom transitions - Douglas Hill","url":"https://douglashill.co/zoom-transitions/"},{"title":"Add iOS 18 Zoom Navigation Transitions To A SwiftUI Grid | The Swift Dev","url":"https://www.theswift.dev/posts/swiftui-zoom-navigation-transition/"},{"title":"SwiftUI | Apple Developer Forums","url":"https://developer.apple.com/forums/topics/ui-frameworks-topic/ui-frameworks-topic-swiftui?page=4&sortBy=activity&sortOrder=DESC"},{"title":"Using the zoom navigation transition in SwiftUI","url":"https://www.createwithswift.com/using-the-zoom-navigation-transition-in-swiftui/"},{"title":"Zoom Navigation Transitions in SwiftUI | Sagar Unagar","url":"https://www.sagarunagar.com/blog/swiftui-zoom-navigation-transitions/"},{"title":"iOS 18 Zoom navigation transition · Issue #25 · hmlongco/Navigator","url":"https://github.com/hmlongco/Navigator/issues/25"},{"title":"[SwiftUI]NavigationTransition. NavigationTransition | by ganeshrajugalla | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@ganeshrajugalla/swiftui-navigationtransition-e44b1032cf0e"}]

Based on my search, here's what I found about the SwiftUI zoom navigation transition availability on macOS:

## The Core Issue

The zoom navigation transition APIs (`navigationTransition(.zoom(sourceID:in:))` and `matchedTransitionSource(id:in:)`) are **not available on macOS**, even though they work on iOS and other Apple platforms.

The broader NavigationTransition protocol is available on macOS 15, but the ZoomNavigationTransition type is marked unavailable on macOS in the current SDK, so keep this code in an iOS or iPadOS availability boundary.

## Platform Availability

The ZoomNavigationTransition API is available starting in iOS 18, iPadOS 18, tvOS 18, watchOS 11, and visionOS 2. Notably, macOS is absent from this list.

For Mac Catalyst, the behavior is nuanced: the zoom transition APIs are available, but only have an effect when using the Scaled to Match iPad setting. When using Optimize for Mac, the traditional iOS-style navigation push and full screen cover vertical transitions will be used instead, which is ironic because a zoom transition would be more Mac-like.

For native macOS, though: the SwiftUI zoom transition APIs are unavailable.

## Why This Is Confusing

The frustrating part is the inconsistency in how the API behaves across platforms. As Douglas Hill notes, it's unclear why we need to write conditionally compiled SwiftUI code to accommodate macOS, while on all other platforms the API exists even if it's ignored. He speculates that this is related to how SwiftUI is internally backed by UIKit on all other platforms, but this feels like an implementation detail that shouldn't leak into the API.

## The Solution: Conditional Compilation

Because the API is marked unavailable on macOS (rather than just being ignored), you need to wrap your code with both `#if os(iOS)` compiler directives **and** `#available` runtime checks. Here's the pattern from The Swift Dev:

```swift
extension View {
    @ViewBuilder
    func zoomTransitionSource<ID: Hashable>(
        id: ID,
        in namespace: Namespace.ID
    ) -> some View {
        #if os(iOS)
        if #available(iOS 18.0, *) {
            matchedTransitionSource(id: id, in: namespace)
        } else {
            self
        }
        #else
        self
        #endif
    }

    @ViewBuilder
    func zoomTransitionDestination<ID: Hashable>(
        id: ID,
        in namespace: Namespace.ID
    ) -> some View {
        #if os(iOS)
        if #available(iOS 18.0, *) {
            navigationTransition(.zoom(sourceID: id, in: namespace))
        } else {
            self
        }
        #else
        self
        #endif
    }
}
```

This approach handles both the macOS unavailability (via `#if os(iOS)`) and the iOS 17 fallback (via `#available`). For iOS 17, the fallback keeps the same navigation and uses the default push animation.

## Key Takeaway

The `#if os(iOS)` guard is **essential** for macOS — unlike a simple availability check, the compiler directive is required because the symbol itself doesn't exist on macOS and would otherwise produce a compile error. On macOS, you simply fall back to returning `self` (no transition modifier), which gives you the standard navigation behavior.


